\begin_layout Subsection
Expansionary policy: decrease in the employer social security rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The decline in employers' social contributions is one another example of
 an expansionist policy through the reduction of the labor cost.
 We simulate a decrease in the employer social contribution of 1 point of
 GDP which matches a decrease of 7.35% uniform rate apparent for all industries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lower cost of labor induced by this shock will play on two levels.First
 on the price level by decreasing the cost of production which leads to
 an increase in the household's real disposable income and thus consumption.
 In the very short run the disinflationary impact and the substitution mechanism
s keep constant investment.
 To this effect combines a lower level of unemployment of 0.1 points in 2010
 year and 1.1 points in 2015 years.
 This is due to the effect of stimulus on demand and from improvement of
 the competitiveness relatively to the rest of the world but also to changes
 in relative prices between inputs resulting in a substitution toward labor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Effects on activity are therefore positive.
 The lower cost of labor and thus production improves competitiveness.
 This results in an improvement in the terms of trade.
 Indeed, the fall in prices led to an increase in exports greater than the
 increase in imports resulting from the increased activity.
 the early imports fall because of improved competitiveness.
 In the medium term, the income effect prevails and imports increase.
 While improving the competitiveness leads to an improvement in the trade
 balance volume , the trade balance in value decreases due to the decrease
 in producer prices: France sells more but cheaper.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the long run, the decline in the unemployment rate generates an inflationary
 effect and therefore a degradation term competitiveness.
 So that long-term positive effect on employment measures fades.
\end_layout

