\begin_layout Subsection
A 50% increase of the oil price
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 50% increase in the oil price is a pure supply shock and has a negative
 impact on the GDP through a reduction of all the component of the demand.
 The reduction of the real disposable income affects the consumption and
 thus the GDP.
 The change in the relative price induces for the producers to switch from
 a more energy-intensive technology toward a more capital-intensive technology.
 We observe that this slight increase in the first years of the investment
 which is due to a substitution effect from the energy input toward the
 capital is offset by the negative effect on the activity and thus is negative
 four periods after the shock.
 Besides this effect on the demand, the oil shock degrades french exports
 by increasing the export prices.
 We can point out that we have a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

naive
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 view on this shock, since in our framework the world prices are exogenous
 and so unimpacted by the oil price shock.
 This leads to an overestimation of the impact on the commercial balance,
 considering that only the France will face a rising in the oil price.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
